[4] North Carolina, rabid fox
Date: 25 Jun 2010
Source: Mooresville Tribune [edited]
<http://www2.mooresvilletribune.com/content/2010/jun/25/county-issues-rabies-alert-after-rabid-fox-bites-s/>


County issues rabies alert after rabid fox bites Statesville man
----------------------------------------------------------------
A 20-year-old man is undergoing treatment after being bitten by a
rabid fox Monday [21 Jun 2010] at a home on Devon Lane in
Statesville, NC. Carla Waller said her niece's boyfriend, the victim,
underwent the 1st series of 6 shots and faces more to protect against
the potential for rabies.

A group of people, including 6 children, were in and around the pool
when a gray fox came through the yard and through the fence
surrounding the pool. The fox went straight for the water as family
members scrambled to get the children out of the pool, she said.

Her father threw a ball toward it, and it ran outside the fence into
some bushes on the other side, she said. Waller's son and the victim
went outside the fence to try to shoo it away, fearing it might come
back into the pool area. The victim grabbed a toy bat and the fox
attacked the bat, then latched onto his leg, biting him on the leg
and ankle, she said.

Iredell County Care and Control officers were called and arrived
within 15 minutes. Officers shot the fox when it charged toward them.
Meanwhile, the victim was taken to Davis Regional Medical Center and
treatment began right away.

On Wednesday [23 Jun 2010], the victim received a call that the fox
was indeed rabid.

Neighbors told Waller they'd seen a fox in the area during the
daytime in the last week or so. That is a clue that the animal might
be rabid, said Iredell Animal Care and Control Director Chris Royal.
It's unusual for foxes to be out during the daytime hours.

Royal said this is the 9th rabies case in Iredell County this year.
So far, the infected animals include the fox, 1 bat, 2 cows, 4
raccoons and 1 skunk.

A city message is being sent to people within a 5-mile radius of
where the fox was captured to warn residents about the rabies
potential. Royal said this underscores the importance of making sure
family pets are vaccinated against rabies.

[Byline: Donna Swicegood]

