[5] Indiantown Florida, rabid bobcat
Date: 12 Jul 2010
Source: TCPalm.com [edited]
<http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2010/jul/12/bobcat-that-killed-two-pigs-in-indiantown-tests/>


Bobcat that killed 2 pigs in Indiantown tests positive for rabies
-----------------------------------------------------------------
A bobcat that killed 2 pigs last week has tested positive for rabies,
according to the Martin County Health Department.

The bobcat attacked several pigs 7 July 2010 at a ranch on Southwest
Foxbrown Road. The pigs that survived the attack will be placed under
quarantine for 6 months.

This is the 2nd case of rabies in Martin County this year. Another
bobcat tested positive for rabies in May [2010] after attacking a
horse in Palm City.

A handful of rabies cases have been reported across the Treasure
Coast. All of Indian River County remains under a rabies alert until
August [2010] following 5 attacks on humans by rabid animals.

Rabies is a virus spread through the bite or scratch of an infected
animal. Any mammal, including humans and domestic animals, can get
rabies. If you get bitten by an animal, wash the wound with soap and
water for at least 5 minutes and seek medical attention.

[Byline: Hillary Copsey]

