[8] Vermont, rabid fox
Date: 8 Jul 2010
Source: Times Argus [edited]
<http://www.timesargus.com/article/20100708/NEWS02/7080380/0/NEWS01>


Rabid fox bites Barre man
-------------------------
A gray fox that bit a man on the ankle last week in Barre was rabid,
Vermont Department of Health biologists confirmed on Tuesday.

The man was bitten 1 July 2010 on Pond Street, said a health
department official. "He got out of his vehicle, was minding his own
business, the fox came out of the blue, bit him on the ankle and sort
of ran away," said Bob Johnson, a public health veterinarian with the
Vermont Department of Health who often deals with rabies cases.

The victim of the bite quickly went to the hospital to begin
treatment, which means he will be fine, said Johnson. "He just got
bit, and shots will keep him safe," said Johnson.

The bite victim was not the only one to encounter the rabid fox,
which was found dead last Friday [2 Jul 2010], said Johnson. "I guess
it tugged at the pant leg of another individual, and another person
found it dead the next day," said Johnson. "There were a number of
people that had some sort of brush with that fox."

A game warden with the Vermont Fish and Wildlife Department was
called in, bagged the dead fox and had it sent to a state lab on the
Fletcher Allen Health Care campus in Burlington, VT, where
microbiologists ran tests on the deceased animal, according to
Johnson. The biologists confirmed the presence of the lethal virus.

Cases of humans getting rabies are extremely rare, said Johnson, with
only one or 2 cases nationally each year. "I think it's safe to say
no human cases of rabies have ever been reported to the Vermont
Department of Health," said Johnson.

The rabid fox is the 26th confirmed case of rabies in Vermont this
year, which means the state is on pace to have an average number of
cases in 2010, said Johnson. This was the 1st case in Barre this year
and the 3rd in Washington County. A rabid bobcat was discovered in
Northfield last month and a gray fox was found in Fayston in April,
according to Vermont Department of Health records. Last year a rabid
skunk was found in Barre.

[Byline: Thatcher Moats]

