[According to the CDC regulations on post exposure prophylaxis
regarding rabies:

Rabies postexposure vaccinations consists of a dose of human rabies
immune globulin and 4 doses of rabies vaccine given on the day of the
exposure, and then again on days 3, 7, and 14. The vaccine is given
in a muscle, usually in the upper arm. This set of vaccinations is
highly effective at preventing rabies if given as soon as possible
following an exposure.

Each state has slightly different regulations regarding treatment of
animals who are vaccinated but exposed. Please check with your state
if your animal has been exposed to a rabid animal. Unvaccinated pets
are generally euthanized. - Mod.TG]
